The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, May 24, 2003  Business Briefs New Delhi, May 23:The government today  invited bids for nine coal bed methane (CBM) blocks for  exploration and production of gas. The nine blocks offered  under the second round of bidding for CBM blocks under the  new exploration licensing policy have a combined resource  of about 500 billion cubic metres of gas, petroleum minister  Ram Naik said. CBM is expected to supplement conventional  sources of natural gas and would help in bridging the domestic  demand-supply gap, Naik added. New Delhi, May 23:The government today  allowed payment of customs and excise duties in the State  Bank of India and Bank of Baroda. Earlier, only the Punjab  National Bank had the permission to collect payment of these  taxes. New Delhi, May 23:The continuous growth  in telephone connections has helped the country touch a  teledensity of 5 per 100 persons, but the digital divide  continues in rural and urban areas. The teledensity has  improved at a rapid pace from 3.6 in March 2001 to 4.9 in  December 2002. Calcutta, May 23:Hindustan Lever Ltd  today extended till June 13 the lockout at its garden reach  factory. The unit employs nearly 1,150 permanent workers  and 350 casual workers. The company first declared lockout  at the factory on March 22, citing labour problems.
